Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear catastrophe to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and includes a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crises ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a centennial flood, combined with design flaws that are normally harmless, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In terms of financial markets, an unanticipated collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivatives and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the base risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, over-investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and bad luck have ensured that the systems have not been able to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – have gone bankrupt, causing a credit freeze in the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that have shaken the global economy.
A Fukushima, the teams of workers are valiantly trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the other hand, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivative products and financial structures, on top of the same active errors.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros by June 1, and the second promises to provide yen.
If a currency loses value relative to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo", a shortening of the English verb repurchase – or repurchase, ndt).
The problem is that the short-term repo cash represents a significant part of the balance sheet of the largest financial institutions, which means that simple financial shocks can affect them strongly.
Some institutions may then be left without repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as with Bear Stearns.
Individually, transactions in derivatives or repos are not particularly blameworthy.
Each one separately transfers the risk in a legitimate way to those who are better equipped to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when they are excessively used by institutions that are vital to the system, they can explode the financial system, due to its design flaws.
Even today, almost 70% of the liabilities of the main American financial companies is made up of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivative contracts or repos with weakened financial institutions may seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. This way, they may decide its fate when, with a bit more time, the company in question would have been able to survive.
Such actions have ruined AIG, Bear Stearns and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos are at the head of the payment queue in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid anyway.
Surely, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions of derivatives and repo actors put them at the head of the payment queue in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, we would expect others to have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in line is often too often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too big to fail, ndt). But, the government is not well-placed to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile ; it is often limited to the regulated market ; and, when economic conditions are good, no official wants to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to solve this shortcoming in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer via the Dodd Frank bill.
But it has not seized it.
If investors in derivatives, repo, and credit-default swaps did not benefit from a favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often that their counterparties be capitalized properly.
They have accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalizations when it was essentially the American government's money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives the risks of the type Fukushima and the risks related to derivatives differently.
Many people are afraid of nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must face security concerns.
But the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and contempt, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding the risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain the risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to foresee nuclear power plants that can keep the fuel rods cool even in the event of a total loss of electrical power.
On the other hand, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damage that the priority of derivatives and repos products could cause in case of financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives products to protect themselves from unexpected changes in oil prices) and others to provide good quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the low incentives for market discipline for the main financial institutions.
It's as if we are reacting to Fukushima by controlling better emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to make the investors in derivatives and repos entirely assume the risk related to their decisions when they make transactions with financial institutions that are vital to the system.
Instead of that, we have only survived the 2008 financial tsunami to rebuild at the same place, with the same financial flaws and with the same defective design.
